WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.870 --> 00:00:04.410
- Welcome to another episode
of Falsehoods of Fitness.

00:00:04.410 --> 00:00:07.370
Today we're gonna be talking
about central nervous system

00:00:07.370 --> 00:00:08.750
fatigue,

00:00:08.750 --> 00:00:13.150
or commonly referred to as CNS fatigue.

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:18.150
So, this was made popular,
the term was made popular

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:22.350
boy, I think in like
the late 80s, early 90s

00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:24.120
by Arthur Jones.

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:27.200
And Arthur Jones is the
founder of Nautilis,

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:30.600
and then it was kinda kept popular by

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:33.170
a body builder named Mike Mentzer

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:36.040
and so what they were talking about was

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:38.320
how there's recovery of muscular tissue.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:39.980
You know I can train my biceps and

00:00:39.980 --> 00:00:42.683
how long does the actual
tissue take to recover.

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:46.590
But, then there's the
neurology associated with

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:50.670
activating that muscle
and there is such a thing

00:00:50.670 --> 00:00:54.550
as the fatigue of the
central nervous system

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:58.570
in respect to when it wants to recruit

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:03.570
as much tissue as, let's say,
before an exercise session.

00:01:04.730 --> 00:01:07.590
So, 'cause effort is very dependent but

00:01:07.590 --> 00:01:09.063
maximum effort,

00:01:09.063 --> 00:01:13.110
the idea was that there
was a certain amount of

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:15.230
time the central nervous
system doesn't want

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:17.730
to engage a certain amount of muscle and

00:01:17.730 --> 00:01:19.340
it turns out that's true.

00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:22.590
But in 2016, a lot of research came out

00:01:22.590 --> 00:01:25.880
that shows that actually
cardiovascular exercise

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:28.360
has a longer window

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:29.924
of

00:01:29.924 --> 00:01:31.160
time

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:33.860
that it takes to reactivate

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:35.310
to the same degree

00:01:35.310 --> 00:01:38.910
some of these tissues called excitability,

00:01:38.910 --> 00:01:43.090
and it turns out that
it wasn't what people

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:44.010
thought it was at all.

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:45.930
It wasn't days or weeks

00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:46.763
that it takes.

00:01:46.763 --> 00:01:49.710
It's really from a
cardiovascular perspective,

00:01:49.710 --> 00:01:51.410
it's like thirty minutes.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:54.500
So, and if you think
logically, that makes sense.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:59.500
Like, if somebody does
heavy resistance exercise,

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.530
let's say they do heavy
squats or even to a more

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:04.933
exhausting degree, like X3 squats,

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:09.360
then they couldn't activate musculature if

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:11.070
they had to run up a flight of stairs or

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:12.820
something like that, they couldn't.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:14.420
Or maybe they would lose their balance

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:17.030
because they can't fire
enough musculature.

00:02:17.030 --> 00:02:20.510
So we know, and soreness
and the inability to

00:02:20.510 --> 00:02:23.490
engage muscle are two
very different things.

00:02:23.490 --> 00:02:25.690
So, do not confuse those two.

00:02:25.690 --> 00:02:26.800
Different.

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:28.540
So,

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.360
when we look at

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:32.870
this, this

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:37.010
and Thomas in 2015, 2016
two different studies

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:41.470
really did a lot to

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:42.700
determine that

00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:46.690
this cardiovascular exercise was more so

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:50.200
the accute changes in the inability to

00:02:51.128 --> 00:02:54.627
to engage or the excitability of

00:02:54.627 --> 00:02:56.800
of musculature.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:02:57.633
But,

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:02.160
probably more to the point,
specifically when looking

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:03.850
at resistance training very,

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:05.580
single session heavy strength training

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:08.500
is what it was described by Latella

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:10.473
in 2016.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:14.650
It looks at what it takes

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:15.483
to go to

00:03:15.483 --> 00:03:16.500
central nervous system fatigue, and

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:19.200
then how long it takes
to recover from it so,

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:22.770
this is just something I
pulled out of the study

00:03:22.770 --> 00:03:26.270
and you can see here's baseline and

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:28.920
this is after somebody
exercises, you can see

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:30.530
the excitability goes down so

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:34.240
baseline is like right where
central nervous system fatigue

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:36.457
is so, right after so

00:03:36.457 --> 00:03:39.670
right, right sorta after the exercise,

00:03:39.670 --> 00:03:41.300
you get about a 10 minute window

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:44.230
where you're not, you're not able to

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:45.580
really engage as much.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:47.800
20 minute window, you're
right back to baseline.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:51.780
30 minutes, you can activate,
you know, just as much.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.560
Above, or at least you're
above the baseline and

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:58.410
then it shows an individual
right about 48 hours later,

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:00.310
there's another exercise session, and

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:03.120
they can engage to a much higher degree.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:06.440
So, central nervous
system fatigue is a thing

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:08.780
but, it's not a thing that
anybody really needs to

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:09.870
worry about because

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:14.773
the actual tissue,
muscle protein synthesis,

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:19.000
is really the bigger issue

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.310
and we have a very good
understanding of that

00:04:21.310 --> 00:04:23.590
now, with muscle biopsy studies.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:28.030
Which is why we know 36
hours is really the window,

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:30.933
and after 36 hours,

00:04:31.837 --> 00:04:33.560
you can train again now.

00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:36.180
With the X3 protocol, we'd wait 48 hours

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:40.680
and that's, that's about it.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:45.020
Now, when it comes to muscle damage

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:49.340
which I'll do another
Falsehoods of Fitness on

00:04:49.340 --> 00:04:51.620
muscle damage and sorta like the idea that

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:53.910
you create micro tears, and micro tears

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:55.320
have to do with growth.

00:04:55.320 --> 00:04:56.873
That is not true, either.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:00.840
There's more micro tears
in musculature when

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:03.480
you run a marathon versus
your weight training session.

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:06.670
And guys who run marathons,
they're not growing any muscle.

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:09.330
So, it's got nothing to do with it, and

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:11.850
that will probably be the
next Falsehoods of Fitness.

